CallId\": \"call_i6ScVfq7mESBvAhOxNhBqvZ3|fc_0775c31a3e99d9ff0169fb3a8498c08195bcfd57925b994f03\", \"toolName\": \"bash\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"text\", \"text\": \"org/apache/pekko/http/impl/engine/http2/Http2AlpnSupport$.class\\norg/apache/pekko/http/impl/engine/http2/Http2AlpnSupport.class\\norg/apache/pekko/http/impl/engine/http2/Http2AlpnSupport.tasty\\nCompiled from \\\"Http2AlpnSupport.scala\\\"\\npublic final class org.apache.pekko.http.impl.engine.http2.Http2AlpnSupport$ implements java.io.Serializable {\\n  private static final java.lang.String H2;\\n  private static final java.lang.String HTTP11;\\n  public static final org.apache.pekko.http.impl.engine.http2.Http2AlpnSupport$ MODULE$;\\n  private org.apache.pekko.http.impl.engine.http2.Http2AlpnSupport$();\\n  public static {};\\n  private java.lang.Object writeReplace();\\n  public java.lang.String H2();\\n  public java.lang.String HTTP11();\\n  public javax.net.ssl.SSLEngine enableForServer(javax.net.ssl.SSLEngine, scala.Function1<java.lang.String, scala.runtime.BoxedUnit>);\\n  public void clientSetApplicationProtocols(javax.net.ssl.SSLEngine, java.lang.String[]);\\n  private boolean isAlpnSupportedByJDK();\\n  private static final boolean isAlpnSupportedByJDK$$anonfun$1(java.lang.reflect.Method);\\n  private static final java.lang.Class $anonfun$1();\\n  private static final boolean $anonfun$2$$anonfun$1(java.lang.reflect.Method);\\n  private static final boolean $anonfun$2(java.lang.Class);\\n  private static java.lang.Object $deserializeLambda$(java.lang.invoke.SerializedLambda);\\n}\\n\"}], \"isError\": false, \"timestamp\": 1778072198673}]}\n3104:[thinking] I need to consider using internal generated public for Scala classes because public top-level test classes might not need an explicit public modifier. I've also noted that the Java invoker has a final package-private top-level class, which isn't a test class, while ALPN is public. There is a potential issue with dynamic-access report classes and the generated test files, but we do have helper Java files. I should check the native image support and ensure that the right properties are set at runtime to avoid build failures. It seems the classpath issues arise from the JavaVersion initialization conflicting with native-image analysis.\n3112:[thinking] I’m wondering if I need to patch the module sourceSet that’s not compiled before the test classes. It seems like the test classes don’t need that patch. But maybe the nativeTestCompile doesn’t depend on compileAlpnPatchJava? Since the test runtime classpath has alpnPatch.output, Gradle should recognize that. I’m uncertain if the sourceSets dependency extends properly, especially with the syntax in Gradle Groovy referring to `sourceSets.alpnPatch.output`. Also, could Checkstyle be an issue with the ALPNExtension's empty method block?\n3118:[recv] {\"type\": \"message_end\", \"message\": {\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"thinking\", \"thinking\": \"**Checking Java and Scala compatibility**\\n\\nI'm looking into whether I need to check if Java compiles with lambda to Scala's Function1. I noticed that Function1.apply returns Object, which is acceptable as BoxedUnit.UNIT. I need to confirm that Scala can access the package-private static class, but it seems fine since they're in the same package. I might have to watch out for Checkstyle issues. Also, it seems I need to update the Java test module and manage classpath issues related to native images. Additionally, I should avoid using `$` in file names and classes, like Http2AlpnSupportTest.\\n\\n**Analyzing Java and Scala integration**\\n\\nI need to consider using internal generated public for Scala classes because public top-level test classes might not need an explicit public modifier. I've also noted that the Java invoker has a final package-private top-level class, which isn't a test class, while ALPN is public. There is a potential issue with dynamic-access report classes and the generated test files, but we do have helper Java files. I should check the native image support and ensure that the right properties are set at runtime to avoid build failures. It seems the classpath issues arise from the JavaVersion initialization conflicting with native-image analysis.\\n\\n**Examining Class.forName in native executables**\\n\\nWhen considering native executables, I see that the implementation of Class.forName uses precomputed classes. However, I'm thinking about how this works for package definitions in java.base. There's a chance that the application class may not be loaded at build time. Since it's on the classpath, the image builder could ignore it if the package belongs to java.base. I'm also wondering if there might be warnings about split packages during this process.\\n\\n**Evaluating Gradle dependencies**\\n\\nI’m wondering if I need to patch the module sourceSet that’s not compiled before the test classes. It seems like the test classes don’t need that patch. But maybe the nativeTestCompile doesn’t depend on compileAlpnPatchJava? Since the test runtime classpath has alpnPatch.output, Gradle should recognize that. I’m uncertain if the sourceSets dependency extends properly, especially with the syntax in Gradle Groovy referring to `sourceSets.alpnPatch.output`. Also, could Checkstyle be an issue with the ALPNExtension's empty method block?\", \"thinkingSignature\": \"{\\\"id\\\":\\\"rs_0775c31a3e99d9ff0169fb3ac22ce481959833168c845ed9a9\\\",\\\"type\\\":\\\"reasoning\\\",\\\"encrypted_content\\\":\\\"gAAAAABp-zrQgMVCH9dIE0vINiwhO4wFPnNNsPDWclgfU_kzcjKFvtaV85Gd0SMoDe06MQTLXrhQGvbRmBR5sMU2VyShE2QTXIXYRVmBa8x-ZkQDDy-gEhfQ432S0MaAgGcLQTfbqp2bAuBYKazFnfs9Ev-eUkXQbt6b9zDrG7BHwG1U3Nptosw0AkjndGFmryGT9mVhtfLnhzUYOxca0oBxq7d8tdtiDNbY4Dw1n-Gte1bck_lQcCqebh0oIZvkXMtyl44uWig1ncUmTgk9tH082uOun-1lRU1OrClfMZfPZUqylF1vwENo9uBCxd_2JklFRTssDMDXD4lXcVSSA6fcyS_3AEkYqDz7HuVAg5e8trF9wDTa4LhQpRLuVeUb7gIvPd_i-VTLmb7IwxUjPpa_09RhYlkA35niAXFGIf9lGorm98qv1EO-mqlL4PHnZcv3