actually exists. If the patch should be applied correctly, I wonder if the dynamic access agent counts JDK classes when there's no exception. I need to inspect the test standard output to determine whether it went to failure or success. Adding an assertion to require failure could help reveal issues, but I might not run it. I need to solve the patch class detection problem first.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Analyzing Java Toolchain Options**\\\\n\\\\nIt seems like this repo is using the Java toolchain version 21, not Graal. Changing `java.specification.version` at launch could be risky, so I’m wary of that. I’m thinking of forcing the JavaVersion object initialization without early initialization, potentially using an isolated classloader. I wonder if we could separate loading for the Pekko classes while addressing the library on the classpath. Forking a new Java process seems convoluted, plus the native test constraints add complexity. Maybe direct reflective methods are an option, but there are limitations there too.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Exploring Java Reflection Options**\\\\n\\\\nI'm considering whether `sun.security.ssl` is really a library or not. Maybe there's a way to utilize `Class.getDeclaredMethods()` in a lambda for this Java helper. I think I might have to manipulate the `JavaVersion.majorVersion` field after initialization to set it to 8. Using `sun.misc.Unsafe` or VarHandle could work, but getting access to Unsafe typically requires reflection, which is tricky. I wonder if the public `JavaVersion` package has a static final int for majorVersion that might be helpful.\\\"}]}\"}, {\"type\": \"toolCall\", \"id\": \"call_0q7GEVU55WEJWksoMrgFdTRo|fc_0775c31a3e99d9ff0169fb3c0304888195b9d7dda1232f9533\", \"name\": \"bash\", \"arguments\": {\"command\": \"javap -classpath /home/vjovanov/.gradle/caches/modules-2/files-2.1/org.apache.pekko/pekko-actor_3/1.4.0/6b5b9d3ea8151f966b5f8ef60e2a2fcc11