Java and Scala compatibility**\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nI'm looking into whether I need to check if Java compiles with lambda to Scala's Function1. I noticed that Function1.apply returns Object, which is acceptable as BoxedUnit.UNIT. I need to confirm that Scala can access the package-private static class, but it seems fine since they're in the same package. I might have to watch out for Checkstyle issues. Also, it seems I need to update the Java test module and manage classpath issues related to native images. Additionally, I should avoid using `$` in file names and classes, like Http2AlpnSupportTest.\\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\\"type\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"summary_text\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"text\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"**Analyzing Java and Scala integration**\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nI need to consider using internal generated public for Scala classes because public top-level test classes might not need an explicit public modifier. I've also noted that the Java invoker has a final package-private top-level class, which isn't a test class, while ALPN is public. There is a potential issue with dynamic-access report classes and the generated test files, but we do have helper Java files. I should check the native image support and ensure that the right properties are set at runtime to avoid build failures. It seems the classpath issues arise from the JavaVersion initialization conflicting with native-image analysis.\\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\\"type\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"summary_text\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"text\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"**Examining Class.forName in native executables**\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nWhen considering native executables, I see that the implementation of Class.forName uses precomputed classes. However, I'm thinking about how this works for package definitions in java.base. There's a chance that the application class may not be loaded at build time. Since it's on the classpath, the image builder could ignore it if the package belongs to java.base. I'm also wondering if there might be warnings about split packages during this process