the Java toolchain version 21, not Graal. Changing `java.specification.version` at launch could be risky, so I’m wary of that. I’m thinking of forcing the JavaVersion object initialization without early initialization, potentially using an isolated classloader. I wonder if we could separate loading for the Pekko classes while addressing the library on the classpath. Forking a new Java process seems convoluted, plus the native test constraints add complexity. Maybe direct reflective methods are an option, but there are limitations there too.\\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\\"type\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"summary_text\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"text\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"**Exploring Java Reflection Options**\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nI'm considering whether `sun.security.ssl` is really a library or not. Maybe there's a way to utilize `Class.getDeclaredMethods()` in a lambda for this Java helper. I think I might have to manipulate the `JavaVersion.majorVersion` field after initialization to set it to 8. Using `sun.misc.Unsafe` or VarHandle could work, but getting access to Unsafe typically requires reflection, which is tricky. I wonder if the public `JavaVersion` package has a static final int for majorVersion that might be helpful.\\\\\\\"}]}\\\"}, {\\\"type\\\": \\\"toolCall\\\", \\\"id\\\": \\\"call_0q7GEVU55WEJWksoMrgFdTRo|fc_0775c31a3e99d9ff0169fb3c0304888195b9d7dda1232f9533\\\", \\\"name\\\": \\\"bash\\\", \\\"arguments\\\": {\\\"command\\\": \\\"javap -classpath /home/vjovanov/.gradle/caches/modules-2/files-2.1/org.apache.pekko/pekko-actor_3/1.4.0/6b5b9d3ea8151f966b5f8ef60e2a2fcc11be146d/pekko-actor_3-1.4.0.jar -p org.apache.pekko.util.JavaVersion | head -80\\\"}}], \\\"api\\\": \\\"openai-responses\\\", \\\"provider\\\": \\\"OCA\\\", \\\"model\\\": \\\"gpt-5.5\\\", \\\"usage\\\": {\\\"input\\\": 1528, \\\"output\\\": 1514, \\\"cacheRead\\\": 73216, \\\"cacheWrite\\\": 0, \\\"totalTokens\\\": 76258, \\\"cost\\\": {\\\"input\\\": 0, \\\"output\\\": 0, \\\"cacheRead\\\": 0, \\\"cacheWrite\\\": 0, \\\"total\\\": 0}